<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-06T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-06T06:00:00-05:00" n="6" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d6">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.512351Double/19: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Edge</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-06T12:00:00+01:00">May 6,
                                1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 6—9 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>130. Your 86, April 24, 5 p.m.<note n="9" xml:id="d6fn9">Not
                                printed.</note> Messrs. Adams, Carroll and Alvord have arrived and
                            are now having conferences which will last for several days with all the
                            representatives of American interests concerned. Informal negotiations
                            with the appropriate French authorities will probably begin on
                            Thursday.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Edge</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>